<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-763-514  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 763 514.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 16 1989 v23 n42 p117(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ten steps to terrible manuals. (avoiding pitfalls in preparingdocumentation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Karten, Naomi.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Guidelines for designing and writing effective training manualsare presented.andP;  Readability is important; paragraphs should bekept short, margins wide, and type size reasonably large.andP;  Poorreadability can conceal critical information, which needs to bedistinguished from information which is merely useful.andP;  Overuse ofmultiple fonts can make manuals unreadable, as can indiscriminateuse of jargon.andP;  Badly-written manuals often bypass the obvious andconfuse users with charts and diagrams that are not properlyrelated to the text.andP;  An effective manual contains examples and iswell-organized.andP;  Useless indexes can be worse than none at all,because cryptic entries make it impossible for students to findwhat they are looking for.andP;  Large or awkward binders discouragestudents from using a manual.andP;  All manuals should be tested beforethey are designated as complete.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Training of EmployeesDocumentationGuidelinesTechnical WritingTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>